  "text": "The protonation-state energies calculated on the basis of this N-state model are shown in Figure 4 (B). The N-like microstate with SB reprotonated from Asp96 has gone from being 1.25 kcal/mol higher than the M-like microstate (off the scale in Figure 4 (A)) to 0.08 kcal/mol lower. This result is consistent with experimental findings that the Mto-N transition involves the reversible reprotonation of the SB from Asp96. [CITATION_1] According to the rules of Figure 3 , this transition is allowed but slow. The next lowest energy state is O-like in having Asp96 reprotonated. According to the transition rules, this state can be reached by a proton transfer from the cytoplasmic side to Asp96, but this process is expected to be slow, thus the relatively long lifetime of N, before the reprotonation of Asp96 that is believed to trigger the change to the O conformer. [CITATION_2] Note that the lowest-energy protonation microstate in the M conformational state was already O-like (Figure 4(A) ), but could not be reached by cytoplasmic-side proton transfer events, because in M the proton affinity of Asp96 is too high to serve as an energetically accessible element in cytoplasmic proton transfer pathway, and direct reprotonation of SB from the bulk is kinetically forbidden.",
